<div id="tribute-info">
  <h2>Time Line</h2>
<p>
1780 - Historians believe Miloš was born in 1780, however controversial arguments suggest he was born in 1783. His family are descendents from the Bratonožići tribe.
</p>
    
<p>
1804 - Miloš Teodorović particpated in the first Serbian uprising with his half-brother Milan Obrenović. 
</p>

<p> 
1805 - Milos married Ljubica Vukomanović. Historians speculate they had many still-births and miscarriages, granting a total number of 17 pregnancies. 
</p>

<p>
1810 - After Milan's death, Miloš adopted his half-brother's surname, Obrenović, and was one of few who stayed in Serbia to face the returning Ottomans.
</p>

<p>
1815 - Miloš led the second Serbian uprising against the Turks. As a result, Serbia gained some autonomy, but remained under Ottoman sovereignty. 
</p>

<p> 
1828-1830 - Miloš invited two distinguised legal specialists to prepare a more suitable criminal and civil code for Serbia.
</p>

<p> 1831 - Sultan of the Ottoman empire gave an imperial edict that recoginised Serbian autonomy for most matters of internal administration. 
</p>

<p>
1835 - After the Mileta Rebellion, Miloš agreed to adopt a very liberal Sretenje Constitution. 
</p>

<p>
1838 - Austria Empire, Russian Empire and Ottoman Empire opposed the Sretenje Constitution. A a result, Miloš abolished the consititution for a less-liberal one led by the three empires. 
</p>

<p class="foot-note"> Further reading about this heroic figure can be found under 'biographies' in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milo%C5%A1_Obrenovi%C4%87_I_of_Serbia" id="tribute-link" target="_blank"><i>Wikipedia</i></p> 
 
</div>      
